  {
    "id": "UgyzNKjnC2LmvR3As8B4AaABAg",
    "author": "@robinvince616",
    "author_channel_id": "UCx5Rahewiv5ENRwcfY61SuQ",
    "text": "Measuring the voltage across a pure LED load is not very informative, since once the voltage becomes high enough to light the LED, the LED will just draw as much current as necessary to prevent it going any higher than the natural forward-voltage drop of the LED. In other words, it will clamp the voltage at that level. A resistive load is much more meaningful when testing, but if you really MUST use an LED, at least place a suitable current limiting resistor in series with it. That will enable you to read both voltage and current simultaneously while ensuring you're not forcing excessive current through the LED.",
    "likes": 1,
    "published_at": "2021-12-05T22:52:59Z",
    "reply_count": 1,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "UgyzNKjnC2LmvR3As8B4AaABAg.9Va5iXUsHdd9VbC64d4zCm",
        "author": "@ThinkingandTinkering",
        "author_channel_id": "UC4AkVj-qnJxNtKuz3rkq16A",
